70. Closures
A Python closure is a nested function that retains access to variables from its enclosing (outer) scope, even after the outer function has finished executing
Scope in Python determines where a specific variable can be accessed or modified in your code.
Local: Variables defined inside a function.
Enclosing: Variables in the outer function of a nested function.
Global: Variables defined at the top level of a script or module.
Built-in: Keywords and built-in functions pre-loaded in Python.

def outer():
